			<ul class="story-list format-xs">
				<li>
					<article>
						<figure class="thumb is-photo">
							<div class="fig-graphic">
								<a href="http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2014/06/karl-rove-and-the-modern-money-machine-108019.html?ml=m_ms"><img src="http://images.politico.com/global/2014/06/20/karl_rove_michael_shay_630x342.jpg" /></a></div>
						</figure>
						<div class="summary">
							<header>
								<p class="category"><a href="http://www.politico.com/p/magazine/tag/special-report">Special Report</a></p>
								<h3>
									<a href="http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2014/06/karl-rove-and-the-modern-money-machine-108019.html?ml=m_ms">Karl Rove and the Modern Money Machine</a></h3>
							</header>
							<div class="meta">
								<p class="byline">By <a href="http://www.politico.com/reporters/KennethPVogel.html" rel="nofollow">KENNETH P. VOGEL</a></p>
							</div>
						</div>
					</article>
				</li>
				<li>
					<article>
						<figure class="thumb is-photo">
							<div class="fig-graphic">
								<a href="http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2014/06/the-myth-of-americas-golden-age-108013.html?ml=m_ms"><img alt="Picketers playing ball outside closed mill during steel srike.  (Photo by Francis Miller//Time Life Pictures/Getty Images)" src="http://images.politico.com/global/2014/06/20/140620_stiglitz_gary_3_getty_630x342.jpg" /></a></div>
						</figure>
						<div class="summary">
							<header>
								<p class="category"><a href="http://www.politico.com/p/magazine/tag/special-report">Special Report</a></p>
								<h3>
									<a href="http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2014/06/the-myth-of-americas-golden-age-108013.html?ml=m_ms">The Myth of America&rsquo;s Golden Age</a></h3>
							</header>
							<div class="meta">
								<p class="byline">By JOSEPH E. STIGLITZ</p>
							</div>
						</div>
					</article>
				</li>
			</ul>
		</div>
	</aside>
</div>
<p>Here&rsquo;s what I say to you: You&rsquo;re living in a dream world. What everyone wants to believe is that when things reach a tipping point and go from being merely crappy for the masses to dangerous and socially destabilizing, that we&rsquo;re somehow going to know about that shift ahead of time. Any student of history knows that&rsquo;s not the way it happens. Revolutions, like bankruptcies, come gradually, and then suddenly. One day, somebody sets himself on fire, then thousands of people are in the streets, and before you know it, the country is burning. And then there&rsquo;s no time for us to get to the airport and jump on our Gulfstream Vs and fly to New Zealand. That&rsquo;s the way it always happens. If inequality keeps rising as it has been, eventually it will happen. We will not be able to predict when, and it will be terrible&mdash;for everybody. But especially for us.</p> <p style="text-align: center;">***</p> <p><strong>The most ironic thing </strong>about rising inequality is how completely unnecessary and self-defeating it is. If we do something about it, if we adjust our policies in the way that, say, Franklin D. Roosevelt did during the Great Depression&mdash;so that we help the 99 percent and preempt the revolutionaries and crazies, the ones with the pitchforks&mdash;that will be the best thing possible for us rich folks, too. It&rsquo;s not just that we&rsquo;ll escape with our lives; it&rsquo;s that we&rsquo;ll most certainly get even richer.</p>

									<footer class="author-bio">
									<p><em>Nick Hanauer is a Seattle-based entrepreneur.&nbsp;</em></p>

									</footer><!--/.author-bio-->
								
						</div>
					
					
		<nav class="story-nav">
			
				<div class="story-actions">
					
						<a class="button continue-reading" href="http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2014/06/the-pitchforks-are-coming-for-us-plutocrats-108014_Page2.html">Continue Reading &raquo;</a>
					
				</div>
			

